Last year the night before my parents flew out to Michigan for a wedding, I had a dream that really spooked me. The first thing I did was called my mom to talk about it in the morning. In my dream, I was surprised/attacked by a giant yellow snake! I like to think that I’m not a superstitious person but when you grow up always surrounded by it… it’s hard to not be swayed by it sometimes. Anyways I was worried that the yellow snake was a bad omen and that maybe my parents shouldn’t travel. So much to my relief, the yellow snake was a good thing. It’s supposed to mean I was going to be pleasantly surprised. And guess what? Right after I hung up with mom, I got an email from Gretchen from @ediblesofla and fast forward here is our garden in their winter issue!! Long story short yellow snake is indeed a good omen. Happy Lunar New Years friends! I used bacillus thuringiensis (bt) one season in all the years I’ve gardened to manage caterpillars. It was during the first season and it was also the last time I used them. Not that I didn’t like it. I can see its purpose if I have to manage tomatoes on a large scale. For our home garden, I don’t think it’s necessary. When the caterpillars die after ingesting the bt, the toxins cause them to stop eating and kills them from the inside. They become these blobs of melting caterpillars. You can google the mechanism if you’re interested but it leaves a  pretty gross mess in the garden. I like to just leave it out for the birds and lizards. Once we get chickens, they’re going to be treats for our feathered friends. #hornworm #hornworms #tomatoplant #tomatoes🍅 #gardenpests #gardenbugs #beginnergardener #beginnergardening #gardeningismytherapy #gardentipsandtricks #gardentips #growingyourownveggies #growingfood #miamigardening #miamigardener #southfloridagardener #southfloridagarden #southfloridagardening #floridagardening #floridagardens #zone10bgardening #gardening #gardenlove #gardeninglife #gardenideas

Hey garden friends! I’ve been playing Cupid in the garden. When nature’s pollinators are a bit busy or are taking shelter from the crazy heat we have this summer, I come in to give a matchmaker’s helping hand. By hand pollinating, I make sure the garden is nourishing us, even when the butterflies and bees are taking a break.

Hand pollination isn’t without its quirks. 🤔 Some flowers have tricky parts, and pollen has a “best before” date. Temperature matters too! High temperatures can also affect pollen and flower receptivity. Soo when it comes to hand pollination…

1. Timing is Everything! Pollinate during the morning when flowers are at their freshest and most receptive.
2. Gently transfer pollen from the male part of one flower to the female part of another. 
3. Use Fresh Pollen. Just like fresh ingredients make the best meals, fresh pollen is key for successful hand pollination. #Zone10bFloridaGarden

Nutsedge is such a pain in the A** to get rid off because of its rhizomes and nutlets buried in the soil. We got to make sure they all come out too when weeding otherwise it’s like a song that never ends… it just goes on and on, my friend. (Any guesses where that’s from? Lol) What we need are patience and perseverance! A whole lot of that, a pair of gloves and a sturdy garden trowel! So…
* Gather your garden tools: gloves, a trowel, and a bucket.
* Gently dig around the nutsedge, loosening the soil.
* Carefully pull out the entire plant, bulbs, rhizomes and all.
* Place the nutsedge in your bucket and burn it! Just kidding. Not really… As long as you don’t don’t compost it, it’s all good. 
* Keep an eye out for new shoots and repeat the process. Eventually it will weaken the plant system enough that it won’t be able regrow. 
And that’s how I’m tackling this sea of nutsedge that has taken over our front garden since the beginning of summer.

The top three tips for growing your own arugula! 
1. Location matters: Arugula loves cool weather. Choose a spot that gets partial shade during the summer, especially in Miami. This helps prevent it from bolting (going to seed) too quickly.
2. Sow Successively: Arugula matures quickly and can be harvested when it’s still young and tender so sow them successively every few weeks to give you a continuous harvest. 
3. Consistent Watering and Well-Drained Soil: Keep soil moist but not waterlogged. Arugula thrives in well-draining soil rich in organic matter. And of course, mulching is always a plus to retain moisture and suppress weeds.

I refreshed one of our pots in the back garden and used coconut husk as mulch. Coconut husk can be an great option, depending on what you need in the garden. Here are some things to consider when using coconut husk as mulch:
It’s great for…
1. Moisture Retention. It helps soil consistently moist and so reducing the need for frequent watering.
2. Weed Suppression. It can suppress weed growth and keep garden beds/containers free from unwanted plants.
3. Slow Decomposition. Coconut husk mulch breaks down slowly and longer-lasting compared to some other mulch types.
4. pH Neutral. It won’t significantly change the pH of soil. Great if you want a specific pH level. 
5. Sustainable. It’s not only renewable resource but also reduces waste since it’s  byproduct of the coconut industry.

Disadvantages 
1. Low Nutrient Content. It doesn’t contribute much to soil fertility and you would need to supplement with fertilizers or compost.
2. Cost. It can be more expensive than some other types of mulch. Not so much in our case, we have plenty coconuts.
3. Coconut husk texture may not be suitable for all garden applications.

1. Space Efficiency: Grow vertically means more valuable horizontal space. Great for urban or small-space gardening.

2. Optimal Growing Conditions: I move our tower around to adjust sunlight exposure, temperature, and humidity to create ideal conditions throughout the year. 

3. Reduced Pest and Disease Risk: Elevated strawberry plants are less likely to come into contact with soil-borne pathogens and ground-dwelling pests.

4. Better Drainage: The towers drainage system prevent waterlogged soil and root rot issues.

5. Cleaner Harvest: Strawberries in a grow tower is less likely to touch the ground and get dirty.

6. Less Weeding: Elevated towers usually have less weed problems and so reduce the need for regular weeding.

7. Someone recommended a soup recipe for calabaza. I saw the number of ingredients listed and said nope I’m sure it delicious but that’s more than I have the energy to procure. This version is comfort in a bowl and the best part is it’s uncomplicated. I want this era of mine atm to be simple or as simple as humanly possible. Here’s how I make Canh Bí Đỏ Sườn Heo - Vietnamese Calabaza and Rib Soup

Ingredients:
- 1 lb pork ribs
- 1 small calabaza (about 1 lb), peeled and diced
- 1 shallot, thinly sliced
- 2 cloves garlic, minced
-1 tsp salt 
-a pinch of sugar 
- 1 teaspoon fish sauce or your favorite flavor enhancer 
- 6 cups water
- Fresh cilantro and green onions for garnish (optional)

Instructions:

1. In a large pot, add the pork ribs and enough water to cover them. Bring it to a boil and let it simmer for about 5-10 minutes. This will help remove impurities from the meat.

2. Drain the ribs, rinse them, and set them aside. Clean the pot.

3. In the same pot, heat some oil over medium heat. Add the minced garlic and sliced onions. Sauté them until fragrant and the onions turn translucent.

4. Add the parboiled pork ribs to the pot and sear them for a few minutes until they develop some color. Season with salt, sugar and fish sauce/flavor enhancer. 

5. Pour in the water. Bring it to a boil and then reduce the heat to a simmer.

6. Add the cubed calabaza to the pot and cook until both the ribs and calabaza are tender, usually about 30-40 minutes.

7. Adjust the seasoning as needed.

I love garlic chives because they’re low-maintenance and is virtually pest free in our garden. They make great companion plants keeping aphids and other garden pests at bay. Here’s some things to consider when growing them for the first time. I’ll be honest, they’re thriving even though I haven’t fertilize or water them regularly after they established in the garden. 

Planting Location: Garlic chives tolerate various light conditions, but they do best in full sun.

Soil Preparation: Garlic chives do best in well-draining soil rich in organic matter.

Watering: Garlic chives like slightly moist conditions. 

Fertilizing: You can apply a balanced, all-purpose fertilizer in the spring to encourage healthy growth but not necessary. 

Harvesting: Use scissors to cut the leaves at the base, leaving some growth for regrowth.

Propagation: They can be grown from seeds but the easiest is to divide mature clumps. They should be divided every so often for healthier plants anyways.

Scallions are easy to grow and are great additions to any kitchen garden. I planted ours from store bought ones and the current batch have been going strong for a couple seasons now. 

Location: Plant scallions in a sunny or partial shade spot with well-drained soil. 

Planting: Scallions can be grown from seeds, sets, or store-bought roots. Plant them about 1 inch deep and 1 inch apart.

Watering: Keep the soil consistently moist since they prefer slightly damp conditions.

Fertilize: Use an all purpose organic fertilizer or compost at the time of planting and side-dress with compost during the growing season.

Thinning: For varieties that multiply by division, thin them to about 3 inches apart to give them space to grow.

Mulch: Use mulch to help retain moisture and suppress weeds.

Harvesting: Start harvesting when they are around 6-8 inches tall. Just cut them just above the soil level. They’ll continue to grow back.

Pests and Diseases: Keep an eye out for aphids and onion flies.

Companion Planting: Great company for carrots, tomatoes, or lettuce

Seasonal Timing: Depending on your grow zone, plant scallions in both the spring and fall. In our grow zone 10b Miami, they grow year round in our garden. #raisedbeds #raisedbedgarden #raisedgardenbeds #vegogarden #scallions #scallion #miamigardening #miamigardener

Propagating lemongrass is pretty straightforward.

1. Pick Healthy Stalks. Look for stalks that are firm, with no signs of disease or pests.

2. Cutting Method. Lemongrass can be propagated from stalks or divisions. Just cut a fresh stalk with roots attached. Trim the top leaves, leaving a few inches of greenery.

3. Rooting in Water. Put the cut end of the lemongrass stalk in a cup of water, make sure the areas where leaves attached are submerged. Change the water often.

4. Rooting in Soil. You can also just plant the cut end directly into a well-draining potting mix. Water and keep the soil consistently moist until roots develop.

Lemongrass prefers a warm environment for rooting. Provide a consistently warm temperature and use a heating mat if needed. Not the case for use in Miami but if you’re doing this elsewhere this time of the year. 

After a few weeks, you should see roots developing. Once the roots are a few inches long, the lemongrass is ready for transplanting.
If you rooted the lemongrass in water, carefully transplant it into a container or the garden once the roots are well-established. If rooted in soil, you can leave it in the same container or transplant it to its final location.

Matured lemongrass can take up a lot of space especially if you don’t harvest often, be sure to give them room.

I water the newly propagated lemongrass regularly until they’re established in its new location.
